english:
  title: A Record of Painted Geese
  author: Im Chun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The monk Huiyun came to me with a painted scroll of geese and asked for my viewing. There were thirty-nine geese in all, yet eighteen displayed forms unlike the others. Their postures—taking flight, alighting, drinking, pecking, rising, settling, stretching, contracting—were rendered with such fineness and completeness that nothing was left wanting. This too stands at the pinnacle of precision and power.

    The monk spoke thus: "This is an heirloom of our temple, though the artist's name is lost to us. Because it is both strange and ancient, I have treasured it long. At first I guarded it jealously as a precious thing. Yet now I hold it lightly. For the gentleman does not cling to possessions—he merely lends them his interest. How much more so for one who has renounced the world? Having lightened the weight of life and death and cast off desire, should we not be foolish to prize a mere painting? Now I return to the south and give this scroll to my younger brother. If you would commit its forms and count to writing, then in days to come, should one read your words without seeing the painting, one could close one's eyes and hold them all in memory."

    I smiled and replied: "The hand that painted these geese must first have conceived their forms complete within the breast. Only then, with brush held firm and swift, could such perfection be achieved. The painter's mind understood the why of it, yet his mouth could not speak it. Though I fashion fair words, how could I fully capture what the painter himself could not express? To preserve even the barest outline of their forms and numbers—there are two facing each other, bowed low with necks intertwined and crossing. Others huddle, their spines barely visible where ridge meets shore. Some rear their wings, straining to rise but not yet airborne. Some bow their heads while their bodies rest. Some stretch their necks and lift their feet. Some step forward while they peck. Some stand alone, utterly still. Some gather in flocks. Some wheel in circles, turning toward the water. Some press shoulder to shoulder, competing for the lead. Some work their feet in rapid motion. Some spread their wings and cast sidelong glances. Some turn their gaze about. Some beat their wings in play. Some slumber. Such, in brief, are they all." Following his words, I merely set down their count in order and gave it to him—this is no formal record, only that.
  footnotes:
    - 'Huiyun (惠雲): A Buddhist monk, likely of Goryeo period. The name suggests a learned practitioner.'
    - 'The thirty-nine geese with eighteen variations: The specific enumeration emphasizes both the work''s comprehensiveness and the artist''s remarkable ability to capture individual character within a species.'
    - 'The scroll''s journey to the south: Reflects the mobility of valuable artworks and monastics during the period, as well as the transmission of cultural treasures.'
    - 'Im Chun''s final disclaimer: His refusal to call this a formal ''record'' (記) is characteristic of Goryeo literati modesty—the piece transcends mere documentation to become philosophical meditation on art, memory, and the limits of language.'
